---
description: Frontend architecture pattern — Svelte 5 SPA, feature folders mirroring backend modules, role-gated routes
globs: ["apps/web/**"]
alwaysApply: false
---

Reference: `ARCHITECTURE.md` Part 2. One Svelte 5 SPA (Vite, no
SvelteKit — no SSR, no file-based routing, no `load` functions) serves
admin, teacher, and parent — never separate apps. Router:
`@keenmate/svelte-spa-router`. Feature folders mirror backend bounded
contexts 1:1, the same vertical-slice philosophy as the backend, not a
type-based split (`components/`, `stores/`, `utils/` as flat catch-alls).

- **A feature's `api.ts` is the only place that calls its corresponding
  backend module's endpoints.** If `outcomes` needs calendar data, import
  a function from `features/calendar/api.ts` — don't issue a raw fetch to
  `/calendar/...` from inside `outcomes/`. This is the frontend equivalent
  of "inject a service, never a repository."

- **Route access is gated through the router's permission system**
  (`router/permissions.ts` — `configurePermissions`/`checkPermissions`/
  `onUnauthorized`, driven by `lib/shared/stores/session.ts`), with
  required-role metadata declared per route in `router/routes.ts`. Don't
  hand-roll `if (role === ...)` checks inside individual page components —
  one place decides who can reach a route.

- **This is client-side enforcement only, and code/comments should say so
  plainly.** There's no server render step — nothing gates a route except
  JavaScript already in the browser. The router's permission check is UX,
  not a security boundary. Every actual enforcement (two-grain scope,
  gravity rule, mapper guards) is backend-authoritative; the API must
  reject an unauthorized request regardless of what the browser rendered.
  Don't write frontend permission logic that implies it's doing security
  work — it isn't.

- **`lib/shared/` is for genuine design-system primitives only** (Button,
  Card, Modal, Badge, layout shell). A domain-specific component
  (`MilestoneSweepGrid`, `PacingBadge`) stays in its owning feature's
  `components/` folder even if it looks reusable — it doesn't move to
  `shared/` on that basis alone.

- **All data fetching is client-side — no `load` functions exist in this
  stack.** Call a feature's `api.ts` from `onMount` or a reactive
  `$effect`; hold results in that feature's rune-based store
  (`$state`). No global state library, no query library pre-adopted at
  this scale.

- **The frontend is never the authority for access control.** It may
  disable/hide UI for a role that shouldn't use it, for UX — but every
  actual enforcement is backend-authoritative. Don't write client-side
  permission logic that duplicates (and could drift from) a backend guard.

- **`routes/parent/` is view-only plus explicit confirm actions** (reply to
  a message, toggle photo consent) — don't add authoring/editing flows
  there beyond what the spec explicitly grants parents.

- **Type drift:** import from `lib/shared/api/generated-types.ts` —
  generated from the backend's OpenAPI spec via `openapi-typescript`, see
  `.cursor/rules/70-api-documentation.mdc` — rather than hand-declaring a
  backend response shape in a feature's `types.ts`. A feature's
  `types.ts` holds only types genuinely local to it (view-model shapes,
  form state), not redeclared API response shapes.

- **Testing is part of definition of done.** Behavior changes in a feature
  need Vitest coverage: unit tests for pure helpers/stores, component tests
  for interactive UI with branching. Mock the feature's `api.ts` — never
  hit the real Nest API from unit/component tests. Run
  `pnpm --filter @eduai/web test` before claiming done. See
  `.cursor/rules/testing.mdc`, `ARCHITECTURE.md` Part 3, and
  `skills/testing-patterns/SKILL.md`.
